sentences: Alex Cartañá (born Alexandra Rosamund Cartañá-Marks; 7 April 1983) is a British singer-songwriter and actress of Spanish origin.
Cartañá first came to fame in 2003 as the featured artist and co-writer of the hit dance record, "Shake It (Move a Little Closer)", which peaked at No. 16 in the UK Singles Chart.
Cartañá returned to complete her fourth and final year at the University of Westminster and graduated in the fall of 2002.
The single, released on 26 August 2003, reached No. 16 in the UK Singles Chart.
Her first solo single released under the EMI label was in April 2004 with "Hey Papi".
An amicable decision was finally made in 2005, to allow Cartañá to walk away from her deal after almost eight months of deliberation.
In October 2004, a third song from Cartañá, "Lost Your Mind", was due for release, however the song was cancelled two weeks prior to the due date.
In 2006, Cartañá teamed up with Paul Smith, a member of 365 Artists Management Company.

Dance projects such "Dig the Vibes" with Cabrera was released through Kidology Records, and a second dance track and co-writer credits was "Funkmanouver", commercially known as "Wait for Me", featured on the Ministry of Sound compilation album, Housexy: Summer in the City, released in March 2007.
In 2015, Cartañá became involved with Disney Junior's animated series The Lion Guard, based on Disney's 1994 film The Lion King.

Early years and influences ==
Cartañá spent her academic years between both English and Spanish educational systems, making her fully bilingual from a toddler.
At 11 years of age, she moved to a strict Spanish Catholic School in the centre of Palma – Colegio San Cayetano.
A Spanish pop and American popular music influence also could be heard during her early years.

Cartañá attended the University of Greenwich in her first year of her BA Business Studies and E-Commerce degree, but would move to the University of Westminster in her second year, after achieving first-class grades.
It was during her time there that she would first enter the music business by working in her sandwich year for a London-based management company, JBS Management & Hardzone Marketing.
Cartañá returned to complete her fourth and final year at the University of Westminster and graduated in the fall of 2002.
In mid-2003, only months after signing with EMI, the opportunity of co-writing and featuring on an already instrumental dance track arose.
Her friendship with Albert Cabrera would lead the way for a second collaboration a few years later.
The EMI years ===
An amicable decision was finally made in 2005, to allow Cartañá to walk away from her deal after almost eight months of deliberation.
Two months after this major transition, Cartañá also left her management team.
In October 2004, a third song from Cartañá, "Lost Your Mind", was due for release, however the song was cancelled two weeks prior to the due date.

Dance projects such "Dig the Vibes" with Cabrera was released through Kidology Records, and a second dance track and co-writer credits was "Funkmanouver", commercially known as "Wait for Me", featured on the Ministry of Sound compilation album, Housexy: Summer in the City, released in March 2007.
